<p style="text-align:justify;">to discharge and carry every thing through the mire for better than a mile; the ground then rises and you have a fine Sandy path to the other end of the Portage; near this Portage the Indians have often found p<span class="AddHand-author">ie</span>ces of Virgin Copper of the purest kind.  At the end of the Portage, the bank is at least forty feet above the lake and is a mixture of sand gravel and Clay, the beach is covered with round whinestone or pavingstone.  Here you have again a full view of the blue expan<span class="AddHand-author">s</span>e of water, rendered more pleasing from having emerged from Surrounding hills and muddy streams.  The coast now bends to the South for more than twenty leagues to the exception of three or four high and rocky points which project northwesterly.  Here are several rivers; in this distance none of which are remarkable until you arrive at the Natonagan, which is fifteen leaves from the Portage and is larger and deeper than any other we have hitherto spoken of.  The beach at its entrance is low and Sandy but the banks soon rise very high of a stiff red Clay, which tinges the water for quarter of a</p>

